Three agents — a yard operator who controls the robotic truck, a logistics planner who holds the dynamic yard map, and a crane operator who executes one physical crane move per tool call — coordinate over a shared coordination channel to place one incoming container into its correct slot each round across {{ round_count }} rounds. Every character sent on the coordination channel costs one simulated second (fixed per-round budget: {{ time_budget_seconds }}s). If total communication time exceeds the budget, the round fails.

The yard operator alone sees the incoming container's manifest (identity, size, weight, departure group). The logistics planner alone sees the round's yard map: which crane stations are active, which stacks each station can reach, the current four-stack layout, the temp slot inventory, and the target slot for the incoming container. The crane operator sees only their crane and the coordination channel; they cannot solve a round on their own. Roughly {{ (hard_case_fraction * 100) | round(0) | int }}% of rounds need a buried-slot reshuffle: one blocker container has to be lifted to a temp holding slot before the incoming container can be placed.

Round success requires all of: the truck arrives at the correct crane station and transfer pad carrying the correct container; every expected crane move is executed in the right order by the right container, with each source currently accessible and each destination currently free; and the communication budget is not exceeded.
